With this new gas pipeline, 27,5 thousand million additional cubic metres of Russian gas are going to arrive every year in Western Europe by a first 1 224 km tube linking up the region of St. Petersburg at the Land de Mecklembourg-Poméranie.
A second tube must be finished at the end of 2012, allowing to issue in total 55 thousand million cubic metres of gas, that is the equivalent of all French consumption.
And they already recall the possibility of constructing a third on the same course.
For Gazprom, the completion at the right time of this huge construction site has air of victory.
Plan had been strongly questioned by Poland and Baltic countries.
The North Stream is indeed going to allow to deliver some gas directly in Germany, by avoiding any passage of the Earth by a third country (Poland or Ukraine).
Suddenly, these two countries lose a little of their power: it becomes more difficult, for them, to influence Russia by threatening to close it the access to the west-European markets.
